      level: 4,
      title: 'Advanced Management of Endometriosis',
      content: `Complex endometriosis requires individualized treatment balancing pain control, fertility preservation, and long-term management.

**Medical Management:**

**NSAIDs:**
| Mechanism: Inhibit prostaglandin synthesis
| Options: Naproxen, ibuprofen, diclofenac
| Efficacy: 60-70% for mild-moderate pain
| Side effects: GI upset, renal toxicity
| Long-acting formulations (studies suggest efficacy)
| Limit: Can't be used long-term

**Hormonal Suppression:**

**Combined Oral Contraceptives:**
| Suppress ovarian function
| Create atrophic endometrium
| Reduce pain in 60-80%
| Skip placebo week for continuous use
| Risk: VTE (especially with smoking)

**Progestin-Only:**
| Norethindrone acetate 5-10 mg daily
| Medroxyprogesterone acetate 10-30 mg daily
| Effective for many patients
| No VTE risk
| May cause irregular bleeding

**GnRH Agonists:**
| Leuprolide, goserelin, nafarelin
| Creates medical menopause
| Add-back therapy (estrogen/progesterone) if needed
| Limit to 6 months (bone loss concerns)
| Side effects: Hot flashes, bone loss

| GnRH Antagonists:|
| Elagolix, relugolix, linzagolix
| Rapid onset, shorter duration
| Add-back therapy included
| Fewer side effects than agonists
| Limited availability

| Aromatase Inhibitors:|
| Letrozole, anastrozole, exemestane
| Reduces estrogen levels
| Limited side effects
| May be combined with progestins

**Surgical Management:**

| Procedure | Indication | Fertility Preservation |
|-----------|------------|---------------------|
| Laparoscopic excision | Pain, infertility | Excision with/without ablation |
| Laparoscopic ablation | Pain control | Excision preferred for fertility |
| Hysterectomy | Pain control | Not an option |
| Oophorectomy | Cancer risk, definitive | Not an option |
| Bowel/Bladder resection | Deep infiltrative | Careful dissection |

**Fertility Preservation:**

| Consideration | Approach |
|---------------|------------|
| Mild disease | Excision with/without ablation |
| Moderate disease | Excision with ablation |
| Severe (Stage IV) | Excision with ablation, consider IVF later |
| Bowel/bladder involvement | Excision of implants, consider specialist referral |
| Ovarian involvement | Cystectomy if possible |

| Outcomes:|
| 40-50% conceive spontaneously after surgery
| 30-40% require ART
| Stage III/IV has lower fertility
| Adhesion reformation is common

| Prevention Strategies:|
| Meticulous surgical technique
| Minimize tissue damage
| Irrigation
| Avoid excessive electrocoagulation
| Hydrodissection
| Adhesion barriers (Seprafilm, Intercede, Adept, Intercede)
| Peritoneal lavage
| Ovarian suspension techniques

| Post-Op Prevention:|
| Hydroxyprogesterone (study promising)
| Hormonal suppression
| Early second-look laparoscopy (controversial)
