      title: 'Advanced Endometriosis Concepts',
      content: `Endometriosis is a complex condition involving genetics, stem cell biology, and chronic inflammation.

**Pathogenesis:**

**Stem Cell Theory:**
| Endometrial stem cells residing in endometrium
| Retrograde transport to pelvis
| Ability to implant and differentiate
| Explains endometriosis in distant locations

**Clonality:|
| Lesions are clonal
| Each implant arises from single cell
| Different metastatic potential
| Somatic mutations in lesions (cancer driver mutations)

**Inflammatory Milieu:**
| Implants secrete inflammatory mediators:
  - Prostaglandins (PGE2, PGF2α)
  - Cytokines (IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α)
  - Growth factors (VEGF, EGF, PDGF)
| Recruited immune cells:
  - Macrophages
  - Natural killer cells
  - Mast cells
  | Neutrophils
| Fibrosis promoted by chronic inflammation

**Pain Mechanisms:**

**Inflammatory Pain:|
| Prostaglandins sensitize nociceptors
| Inflammatory cytokines activate nerves
| Central and peripheral sensitization
| Reduced pain threshold

| Neurogenic Inflammation:|
| Substance P released from nerve endings
| Activates mast cells
| Increases vascular permeability
| Enhances pain signaling

**Visceral Hyperalgesia:|
| Increased sensitivity to pain
| Heightened response to stimuli
| Organ-specific patterns:
  - Bladder urgency/pain
  - Bowel pain/cramping
  - Uterus cramping

**Fibrosis Mechanisms:**
| TGF-β stimulates fibroblast activation
| Fibroblasts deposit collagen
| Extracellular matrix accumulation
| Tissue remodeling and scarring
| Adhesion formation

**Advanced Imaging:**

**MRI for Deep Infiltrating Disease:|
| Superior for deep infiltrative endometriosis
| Can detect:
  | - Rectovaginal septum
  | - Uterosacral ligament disease
  | | - Bladder/bowel involvement
| 99% sensitivity for deep disease

| Limitations:|
| Cost considerations
| Limited availability
| Not needed for all cases

| Ultrasound:|
| First-line imaging
| Detects endometriomas
| Limited for deep peritoneal disease
| Operator-dependent

| Markers:|
| CA-125: Non-specific marker
| Anti-Müllerian Hormone (AMH): May be elevated
| Serum and peritoneal fluid levels
| Not routinely used clinically

